The entrees were amazing, sauce on the Branzino was so good, and the Kabocha pumpkin was huge! We also got a few apps/sides, I could eat the DIY spicy tuna daily.

I went for dinner with my wife last night for the first time.  We absolutely loved Yoshi's Cafe: the food was of super high quality, the service as nice and careful as one may want. All in a laid-back, unpretentious setting that makes you feel at home.  We can't wait to go back!

The restaurant is beautiful, the staff was so great. Everything was served in disposable containers except the glasses. So very safe for this covid environment. I ordered the Mac n cheese with the smokedbrisket, it was  good. I was expecting to taste more of a smokiness in the brisket, it was tender and a good size portion. The mac and cheese was pretty standard made with cavatelli noodles which I love. Tab was about $30.00, All in all very nice.

Yoshi’s Cafe is hands down the best service experience I’ve ever received in Chicago. Their staff are incredibly kind and so attentive even throughout the craziness of covid. If I could give them 11/5 stars I would. AMAZING food, like hit you in the gut good.

Delicious local spot that is really taking covid precautions very seriously and well spaced out.  The mac and cheese is rich and creamy.  The ribs were pretty good, but the rice pilaf that came with them was incredible.  The real star of the food that I tried was the Smash burger (cooked pink). It was juicy, well cooked, and the toppings complimented it perfectly (the pickles are so good)  The service was also very quick and attentive.

A restaurant with history and pride. Not only the food here is top-notch, the staff including the host/owner Nobuko san is amazing. I cannot wait to go back.

I’ll start this review by saying my only regret is I’m not capable of eating more. Yoshi’s quickly became a neighborhood favorite as I attempt to eat my way through this menu. I thrive on fresh, thoughtful food and this is it. My favorites include the pâté, grilled shishito peppers, and the wagyu burger. HOW is this burger so good? I’m a fan of the drink menu - the lychee martini is a must, and the wine selection is impressive. The atmosphere is delightful. I especially enjoy dining on the patio during the warm months. The staff is always super attentive and knowledgeable about the offerings. I love this place so much we chose Yoshi’s for a birthday dinner of six, which definitely helped me on my quest to complete the menu!
Foie Gras was amazing, and everyone else enjoyed their food as well. French fries with truffle vinegar? Yum!

we went last night for Chicago restaurant week and everything was fantastic. The endive salad was delicious and the fish was outstanding. Had crispy crust and the sauce was light and just delicious.  the service was extremely slow and it wasn't very busy when we got there. I don't think it was slow in a bad unattentive way I think that's just the pace of the restaurant. So if you're in a rush I would for sure let them know and make sure they can accommodate you.

First,  the service is spectacular! Super courteous and respectful. 2and, the food.... oh the food!! My first visit here , certainly will NOT be my last! Nothing was at all disappointing. Keep it up Yoshi's!! You're doing a fantastic thing here!
Good food!

Was my first time at Yoshi's for a private birthday party. The service was EXCELLENT and the staff was super friendly and all the food was nothing short of DELICIOUS! From the appetizers to the drinks to the main course! It was an AMAZING experience!

Long time Chicago chef owned restaurant until Yoshi died a couple of years ago. His wife continued it and kept it going well. Their son has taken over as chief recently and he has really done a great job of modernizing the menu. The good was great. The waiters are still there and reliable in service. They, and the kitchen, are flexible with orders.  AND, the martini's are still good.

Yoshi's is a very welcoming neighborhood spot that happens to serve very satisfying Japanese-French-American fusion cooking. From the cocktails to dessert we loved everything we had. Our waiter googled the pastry we had (a pear chiboust) so he could tell us some of its history. A very friendly place.
My 1st time eating here.  The fish was AMAZING! The service was great!  Jason, our server was friendly and very attentive. I would definitely eat here again!

Started as a five or so table French place. Grew up to be a neighborhood mainstay. Had mama's birthday brunch there! Was not disappointed by any means. They even crafted a 88th birthday cake for her! Yoshi has passed on but Nobuko-san keeps this place going strong!
One of our regular stops for dining. The food is delish. Classic Asian and continental fusion cuisine. Service is great.

while I was in the area I decided to stop in for some brunch on a Sunday afternoon with 3 of my friends.  To our surprise, there wasn't much people dining in (most brunch places usually are packed on Sunday afternoons).  This didn't deteriorate us since this place was so highly rated.For food, I started off with the Japanese pumpkin ravioli.  Don't be alarmed when you see the $8 price tag per piece because the taste alone makes it worth it.  It's not your typical ravioli but more of their take on it.  The Japanese pumpkin is served on a bed of garlic goat cheese sauce and topped with a parmesan cheese dome.  The presentation wasn't all that exciting, but the flavors were on point.  For my entree, I went with the apple pancake soufflé.  It was topped off with whipped cream (which I opted out of), fresh mixed berries, and then finished off with powder sugar.  The texture of the pancake soufflé was light and airy, yet dense enough to resemble a pancake.  I don't know how they do it!  I even enjoyed all the fresh berries on top.
Consistently great food and service.

In my opinion the best Chicago restaurant. Food is top notch. The place has real class and you can't manufacture that. I love this apanese French fusion style of cooking. Cream of mushroom soup with a toast spoon is must at brumch.

Yoshi's Cafe had quite the (good) reputation around 10 years ago when I first moved to the city. I went for a meal back then before I had really found my passion for great food, and thought the meal was great. Fast forward to today, and all I can say is that Yoshi's Cafe still maintains a good restaurant and menu, but it's fallen quite a bit compared to it's peers (upscale dining). Great service helps, but time and better options around the city have left Yoshi's largely behind.

It's not the same without Yoshi, but it's still special. The service was perfect, and the room is great. I wasn't impressed by the Loup de Mere. The fish was cooked perfectly but the sauce was over powering. I can think of more interesting places to spend $100+ per person for dinner.

Yoshi's cafe is an interesting fusion of French/Asain and they execute it well. I went there on a Friday night at 9 and we still were sat immediately. We started with the Tartare which was amazing. I had the Steak, topped with Arugala, Truffle Oil, and Chocolate covered baon. The combination was very interesting and surprising tasted good together. My steak, literally, cut like butter. My friend had the Cheeseburger which tasted amazing. The fries that we shared also were great.

AMAZING meal & equally great service!  Unpretentious, but warm, & inviting, in all ways a top shelf experience.  The menu is inventive, we'll thought out, fresh, and classy.  We ordered the tuna tartar (from specials menu), lobster bisque, gazpacho soup (special), & jumbo sea scallops (special) .  The lobster bisque is unlike anything I have ever had before.  Tuna tartar was the best ever.  Honestly one of the most enjoyable dining experiences I have ever had top to bottom.  Please go!  You won't be disappointed.
